---

Reviewed by Opus 4.7 via manual /review-crate invocation. The crate
mirrors Rust's unstable `allocator_api` (the README explicitly says
"mostly verbatim copy from rust repository"). 17 .rs files, ~8k
lines total; biggest are boxed.rs (2272), vec/mod.rs (3232),
raw_vec.rs (642).

Findings:
- No build.rs, no proc-macro, no Command/network/include_bytes!
- 277 `unsafe` occurrences, 54 `// SAFETY:` comments
- src/stable/alloc/mod.rs (the Allocator trait) has well-written
  SAFETY comments at every unsafe block
- src/stable/boxed.rs has 75 unsafe blocks (excluding doctests) but
  only 1 SAFETY: comment — many obvious cases stripped from the std
  original (e.g. lines 368, 395, 472, 545, 571)
- src/stable/raw_vec.rs has 8 unsafe blocks and zero SAFETY:
  comments
- Published tarball contains no CI config (no .github), so miri
  presence in upstream CI cannot be verified from the source bytes
  alone; assuming none for the rating
- Cargo.toml gates pure-`alloc` vs nightly behind features cleanly;
  `nightly` feature re-exports core/alloc directly
- Optional serde dep; license MIT OR Apache-2.0; author zakarumych
  (rendy/gfx-rs)
- Rating: neutral. Capped by missing SAFETY comments throughout
  boxed.rs and raw_vec.rs (rubric §2). Independent §3 cap (no
  observable miri) also lands at positive. Neutral dominates.
